  <li id="comment-44914" class="comment even thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn"><a href="http://webloomhere.blogspot.com/" class="url" rel="ugc external nofollow">Margaret Bloom</a></cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2016/01/quince/#comment-44914"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-01-11T09:01:56-05:00">Monday, January 11, 2016 at 9:01 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>At university I once destroyed my scrabble opponents by landing the word quince on a triple word score.  When my friends challenged the word, I was happily able to tell them that I had cooked one in our very own kitchen earlier that day.  I think I may have only cooked up a quince once since then.</p>
<p>I&#8217;ve seen quinces in the market twice last week and was sorely tempted, but reached for apples instead, to make Judy Rodgers&#8217; roasted apple sauce.  Now that you&#8217;ve inspired me, I will have to run out and actually buy one (or two or three).  </p>
<p>Thanks for the inspiration.<br />
mb</p>
    </div>

