  <li id="comment-45138" class="comment even depth-2">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Pamela</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2016/01/quince/#comment-45138"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-01-24T01:26:03-05:00">Sunday, January 24, 2016 at 1:26 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>We have a quince tree here in Tasmania too, that is about 6 years old now. I&#8217;m looking out the window and, despite the drought, has heaps of tennis-ball sized fruit growing on it. I&#8217;m thinking that I&#8217;ll be super busy in about April if they all make it. I also use the slow cooker and star anise, cinnamon, cloves and lemon rind, to get ruby red spicey quinces. We eat them like crazy, and I bottle (can..?) the excess. Perfect in the dreary winter! I make quince cheese too, but got sick of getting splatted with molten jammy quince, so now make it to a paste and put it in jam jars for crackers and cheese. The smell of quinces in a bowl is devine.</p>
    </div>

