  <li id="comment-45169" class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Rochelle</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2016/01/quince/#comment-45169"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2016-01-24T18:03:53-05:00">Sunday, January 24, 2016 at 6:03 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>This may be the laziest cooking advice ever regarding quinces but here it is: I just scrub and rinse whole quinces and I don&#8217;t peel or core or cut them up until they have stewed for about 1 hour. I just cook them whole in sweetened water &#8211; your choice of white or brown sugar or honey. Or maple syrup or a mixture. I add a dash of salt to the water too. Anyway,after an hour, I poke thequince(s) with a knife tip to determine if it is soft enough to peel, cut, core. I fish out the fruit and let them cool. Then I quarter them, peel, and core them. Then you can cut them up as you choose and put them back into the liquid. Add whatever spices you like -cinnamon stick, cardamom, nutmeg, &#8230; Cook them until soft and rosy, another hour or longer. After you have par cooked them, you may want to use them to make a middle eastern dish of stuffed quinces.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reply">
      <a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-45169' data-commentid="45169" data-postid="8993" data-belowelement="comment-45169" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Rochelle" aria-label='Reply to Rochelle'>Reply</a>    </div>
